      commentary: `The sun is the simplest and most perfect analogy for the kṣetrajña. One sun, one source of light — and by its light, all the countless objects of the world become visible. Without the sun, there is nothing to see, no matter how real the objects might be. The objects don't produce their own visibility; they borrow it from the sun. And the sun is not affected by what it reveals. A garbage heap illumined by the sun does not make the sun foul. A corpse in sunlight does not make the sun less luminous.\n\nKṣetrī — the one who possesses the field, the knower of the field. This consciousness illumines the entire kṣetra. By its light, the body is known, the mind is known, emotions and perceptions and memories are known. Nothing in the kṣetra generates its own awareness — each element borrows awareness from the kṣetrajña the way each object borrows visibility from the sun.\n\nThis analogy also contains the teaching of non-dual unity. There are countless fields — countless bodies and minds across all of creation. But the kṣetrajña, like the sun, is one. Not many separate consciousnesses each illumining their own particular field, but one consciousness present in all fields simultaneously. The sun doesn't divide itself: one ray for each object. It simply shines, and everything visible is visible by that one light. The kṣetrajña simply is, and every kṣetra is known within that single awareness.`
