      commentary: `The chapter closes with the instrument of liberation named explicitly: jñāna-cakṣu — the eye of wisdom. The ordinary eyes see bodies. The mind sees thoughts. But none of the usual instruments of perception can see the kṣetrajña. There is a different kind of seeing required — a direct apprehension that is itself an act of the kṣetrajña, not of the kṣetra.\n\nAntaram — the distinction, the gap between them. Knowing this gap is not intellectual knowledge of a concept. It is the lived recognition of the difference between observer and observed in one's own moment-to-moment experience. When you notice pain, you also notice that something notices the pain. When you watch a thought arise, you also notice that something watches. The gap between the watching and the watched — when that is seen clearly, constantly, without conceptual overlay — that is jñāna-cakṣu.\n\nBhūta-prakṛti-mokṣam — liberation from the nature of beings. The bondage that generates suffering and rebirth is precisely the confusion of kṣetra and kṣetrajña — thinking you are the field when you are the knower of it. When that confusion ends, the bondage ends. Not as a future event but as an immediate consequence of the seeing. Those who know with wisdom's eye this distinction — yānti te param — they go to the Supreme. The entire architecture of Chapter 13, from the field and its elements to the light of lights seated in every heart, has been in service of this one seeing. The eye that sees is already what it seeks.`
